  "game_explanation": "This three-player, three-round bargaining game centers on exchanging red and green chips with asymmetric private values on red and a common value on green. Every player starts with 10 red and 10 green chips. Green is worth $0.50 to everyone, so it is a natural medium of exchange and safe store of value. Red is privately valued: dog=$0.30, buffalo=$0.10, cat=$0.40. From an outside analyst perspective, cat values red the most, dog is intermediate, and buffalo values red the least; buffalo is also the relatively red-poor type in terms of marginal value and will be the most willing seller of red. However, in the game each player only knows their own values and infers the others’ preferences by observing which trades are proposed or accepted. Because green is common value and relatively high at $0.50 compared with most red valuations, all players will be wary of giving up green unless they believe they are getting red that is at least as valuable to them in expected terms. The main surplus opportunities lie in transferring red away from buffalo (who values it at $0.10) toward dog ($0.30) and especially cat ($0.40), in exchange for green flowing in the opposite direction. Strategic uncertainty arises because a proposer cannot choose which acceptor they trade with if both non-senders accept; instead, one is randomly chosen. This means a proposer must design offers that are acceptable to at least one plausible partner, but that do not accidentally give away favorable terms to a different acceptor with a higher or lower red value than anticipated. As the game proceeds, players update beliefs about others: a player who eagerly buys red with green likely values red highly; a player who tries hard to sell red for green is likely to have a low red value. Since there are only three rounds with one proposal per player per round, timing matters: players have limited chances to execute beneficial trades. Early offers tend to be more exploratory and conservative, while later offers can become more aggressive if someone is still far from their preferred portfolio, especially the high-red-value player (cat) trying to acquire red and the low-red-value player (buffalo) trying to unload it. The outside reconstruction below assumes individually rational behavior, simple heuristics based on own values, and gradual learning from observed accept/decline patterns, generating a plausible full path of offers and acceptances under these rules.",
