      "round_explanation": "By the start of round 1, some information has been revealed. Dog offered to pay 1 green per red and buffalo accepted, signaling that buffalo is relatively willing to give up red for green (consistent with a low red value). Buffalo then sold red to cat at a rate of 3 red for 2 green, which both increases buffalo’s green holdings and suggests buffalo is actively unloading red; cat’s acceptance at that price signals a relatively high red valuation. Cat’s own attempt to buy 3 red for 3 green was rejected by both others, showing that neither dog nor buffalo is willing to sell red at 1:1 green/red under current beliefs and holdings. Now dog has moderately more red and slightly fewer green; buffalo has fewer red and more green; cat has more red and fewer green. Given these patterns, dog and cat both know buffalo is the likely red seller. Cat, valuing red the most, will want to keep accumulating red but must preserve enough green to buy from buffalo. Dog, who has already made a profitable trade from buffalo, will be more cautious about overpaying and may also try to sell some red at an advantageous price if cat appears hungry for red. Buffalo will continue trying to trade red for green while not giving away too much after learning that cat is eager for red.",
