{
  "game_explanation": "This is a three-player bargaining game with two chip types: GREEN (common value $0.50 for everyone) and RED (privately valued: $0.10 for cat-orange-7489 and camel-green-9744, $0.30 for buffalo-red-8335). Everyone starts with 10 GREEN and 10 RED. Because GREEN is more valuable than RED for all players, all agents prefer to hold more GREEN and fewer RED, but buffalo-red-8335 is relatively more willing to hold RED than the others. Strategic tension arises because proposals must involve offering one color and requesting the other, and the proposer cannot choose which responder, if multiple accept, will trade with them. Each player sees all past trades and chip holdings but does not know others’ private RED values, so they infer others’ valuations from which trades they accept or reject. Efficient surplus-creating trades generally move RED toward buffalo (who values it more) and GREEN toward cat or camel in exchange, but cat and camel are symmetric in values, which creates uncertainty for proposers: any trade attractive to one may also be attractive to the other, risking random partner selection. Over three rounds with one proposal per player per round, players will experiment early with modest, value-improving trades to learn about others’ RED valuations, then potentially escalate to larger, more directional trades once they infer that buffalo likely values RED more. Cat and camel will tend to offer RED and demand GREEN; buffalo will tend to offer GREEN to acquire undervalued RED, but must leave enough surplus for the counterpart given the public common-value GREEN. Bargaining power is limited by the short horizon (only three rounds), by the randomness when multiple players accept, and by the requirement that each trade must be individually value-increasing for both sides given their beliefs at the time.",
  "rounds": [
    {
      "round": 0,
      "round_explanation": "At the start of round 0, all players hold 10 GREEN and 10 RED and have no information about others’ private RED values. Everyone knows GREEN is worth $0.50 to all, but only buffalo-red-8335 privately knows they value RED at $0.30, while cat and camel each value RED at $0.10. Early proposals are likely to be small, exploratory, and roughly value-neutral from the proposer’s perspective, to see who is willing to take the less-preferred color. Cat and camel will tentatively try to shed RED for GREEN; buffalo will test exchanging some GREEN for RED if the terms are favorable. Because responders act simultaneously and the realized partner is random if multiple accept, proposers face uncertainty about which counterpart they will actually trade with, so they typically choose terms that are just attractive enough to at least one expected responder while not being too generous.",
      "turns": [
