cted.\n4) Short horizon: with only three rounds and one proposal per player per round, the game is short. Players are unlikely to invest heavily in signaling and instead try to secure positive-value trades whenever they see a sufficiently good deal, especially in later rounds when there are fewer remaining opportunities.\n\nGiven the private values, efficient patterns (from the analyst’s perspective) would involve moving red chips toward Alligator and Tiger (who value red highly) and blue chips toward Otter (who values blue highly), often financed with green chips. However, because the players only see their own payoffs, we should expect imperfectly efficient trades: players will sometimes trade at rates that look suboptimal from the outside but are still privately beneficial under their beliefs. Over the three rounds, the likely trajectory is: cautious, exploratory trades in round 0; somewhat more aggressive, value-seeking trades once some preferences are inferred in round 1; and more opportunistic, endgame trades in round 2, with players using their remaining low-value chips and some greens to grab whatever high-value chips they can still get.",
