eferred partner; this discourages extremely generous offers that would be attractive to everyone. Conversely, responders must decide whether the offered deal is clearly profitable in terms of their own values or whether to decline in hopes of better terms later, under the constraint that there are only three rounds and three turns per round.\n\nGiven this is the first negotiation game, players are unlikely to be highly sophisticated about equilibrium reasoning. They will more likely behave in line with simple heuristics: avoid giving away chips they privately consider very valuable, be willing to part with chips they like least, and demand more of the chips they suspect others might undervalue. Early turns are exploratory and cautious; later turns build on newly revealed patterns and the dwindling opportunity to trade before the game ends. As the final round approaches, responders may accept smaller gains they would have rejected earlier, because there is little time left to find a better offer. Overall, we should expect a few mutually beneficial trades that move red away from owl and blue away from lion, balanced against a number of declined offers that were either too one-sided or misaligned with others’ hidden preferences.",
